V'''Laurie Ann (L.A.) Paul''' is a professor of [[philosophy]] at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], having previously taught at [[Yale University]] and the [[University of Arizona]].<ref>[http://lapaul.org/vita.pdf "L.A. Paul: Vita"]</ref><ref>[http://leiterreports.typepad.com/blog/2008/03/notre-dame-make.html "Notre Dame Makes Bid for Arizona's Paul: Leiter Reports, A Philosophy Blog"]</ref> She is best known for her research on the counterfactual analysis of [[Causality|causation]] and the concept of "transformative experience."<ref>[http://www.newappsblog.com/2011/05/new-apps-interview-la-paul.html "New APPS Interview: LA Paul"]</ref><ref>[http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424127887324432404579052901271445142?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10001424127887324432404579052901271445142.html&fpid=2,7,121,122,201,401,641,1009 "Alison Gopnik, Is it Possible to Reason About Having a Child? (The Wall Street Journal)"]</ref>\u000a\u000a== Biography and career ==\u000a\u000aPaul graduated from [[Antioch College]] in [[Yellow Springs, Ohio]] in 1990 with a B.A. in [[chemistry]]. Before going to graduate school, Paul corresponded with a number of philosophers about their work, including [[Nancy Cartwright (philosopher)|Nancy Cartwright]] and [[Lynne Rudder Baker]].<ref>[http://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2011/05/opportunity-cost.html "Opportunity Cost: Marginal Revolution"]</ref>  In 1999, Paul graduated from [[Princeton University]] with a Ph.D in [[philosophy]], where she wrote a [[Thesis|dissertation]] titled ''Essays on Causation'' <ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/Essays_on_Causation.html?id=NrfltgAACAAJ '"Essays on Causation"]</ref> under the supervision of [[David Lewis (philosopher)|David Lewis]].<ref>[http://www.newappsblog.com/2011/05/new-apps-interview-la-paul.html "New APPS Interview: LA Paul"]</ref>\u000a\u000aPaul taught at [[Yale University]] from 1999 to 2001, and at the [[University of Arizona]] from 2001 until 2008, before moving to North Carolina.  She has also held appointments at the [[Australian National University]] and at the [[University of St. Andrews]].\u000a\u000aShe is married to the sociologist and blogger [[Kieran Healy]].<ref>[http://thinkprogress.org/yglesias/2008/08/23/189128/mereological_update/ "Think Progress: Matthew Yglesias"]</ref>\u000a\u000a== Philosophical work ==\u000a\u000aPaul's principal research interests are in [[metaphysics]] and the [[philosophy of mind]]. Her work focuses on causation, [[mereology]], the philosophy of [[time]], and related topics in [[Phenomenology (philosophy)|phenomenology]], the [[philosophy of science]], and [[philosophy of language]]. Her work in [[ontology]] and mereology develops a distinctive view of objects as fusions of property instances.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/Metaphysics.html?id=0vGzcQAACAAJ "Metaphysics: 5 Questions (Interview with LA Paul)"]</ref> Her article "What You Can't Expect When You're Expecting" develops the notion of transformative experience and explores its consequences for the possibility of rational decision-making.<ref>[http://www.npr.org/blogs/13.7/2013/03/11/173977133/is-having-a-child-a-rational-decision "Tania Lombrozo, Is Having a Child a Rational Decision? (NPR)"]</ref><ref>[http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/apr/06/this-column-change-life-transformative-experiences "Oliver Burkeman, This Column Will Change Your Life (The Guardian)"]</ref><ref>[http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/books/2013/04/graduate-school-advice-impossible-decision.html "Joshua Rothman, The Impossible Decision (The New Yorker)"]</ref>\u000a\u000aShe has written more than twenty articles, and is the editor of ''Causation and Counterfactuals'',<ref>[http://mitpress.mit.edu/books/causation-and-counterfactuals "Causation And Counterfactuals"] MIT Press, ISBN 978-0-26253-2563</ref> co-author of ''Causation: A User's Guide'',<ref>[http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780199673445.do#.UIniW7Rpfls "Causation: A User's Guide"] Oxford University Press, ISBN 978-0-19-967345-2.</ref> and author of ''Transformative Experience.''<ref>http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780198717959.do</ref>\u000a\u000a==Awards==\u000aPaul has received the following awards:\u000a* A grant from the [[John Templeton Foundation]] to study religious and transformative experience.http://news.nd.edu/news/49074-notre-dame-and-unc-chapel-hill-philosophers-to-examine-religious-and-transformative-experiences/\u000a* A [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] (2014).<ref>[http://www.gf.org/fellows/17652-l-a-paul "L.A. Paul - John Simon Guggenheim Foundation"]</ref>\u000a* An ''NHC Fellowship'' (2011-2012) from the [[National Humanities Center]].<ref>[http://nationalhumanitiescenter.org/fellowships/1112fell.htm "NHC Fellows and Their Projects, 2011-2012"]</ref>\u000a* An Institute for Advanced Study Research Fellowship at the [[Australian National University]].<ref>[http://philrsss.anu.edu.au/node/619 "RSSS Philosophy, Australian National University"]</ref>\u000a\u000a==Selected works==\u000a* {{cite journal | year = | title = What You Can't Expect When You're Expecting | doi = 10.11612/resphil.2015.92.2.1 | journal = Res Philosophica | volume = 92 | issue = 2| pages = 1\u201323 }}\u000a* 2014. ''Transformative Experience''. Oxford University Press, ISBN\u000a* 2013. ''Causation: A User's Guide''. Oxford University Press, ISBN 978-0-19-967345-2.\u000a* 2010. "Temporal Experience". [[The Journal of Philosophy]] CVII (7) 333-359. Reprinted in ''The Future of the Philosophy of Time'', edited by Adrian Bardon. New York: Routledge (2012).\u000a* 2010. "The Counterfactual Analysis of Causation". In ''The Oxford Handbook on Causation'', edited by Helen Beebee, Christopher Hitchcock and Peter Menzies Oxford University Press, ISBN 978-0199279739.\u000a* 2006. "Coincidence as Overlap". [[Noûs]], 40: 623-649.\u000a* 2004. ''Causation and Counterfactuals''. Co-edited with Ned Hall and John Collins. MIT Press, ISBN 978-0-26253-2563.\u000a* 2002. "Logical Parts". Noûs, 36: 578-596. Reprinted in ''Metaphysics'' volume v, edited by Michael Rea. Routlege 2008, ISBN 978-0-415-39751-3.\u000a\u000a==Notes==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* [http://lapaul.org L.A. Paul's Homepage]\u000a* [http://philosophy.unc.edu/people/faculty/laurie-a.-paul L.A. Paul's Homepage at UNC Chapel Hill]\u000a* [http://vimeo.com/15792058 Conversation on Causation and Counterfactuals with Ned Hall on Philosophy TV]\u000a* [http://www.prx.org/pieces/79729-what-might-have-been Interview on the radio show "Philosophy Talk" with Ken Taylor and John Perry]\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Paul, L.A.}}\u000a[[Category:American academics]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Academics of the University of St Andrews]]\u000a[[Category:American women philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Causality]]\u000a[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of mind]]\u000a[[Category:Antioch College alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Ontologists]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of science]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of language]]\u000a[[Category:Princeton University alumni, 1990\u201399]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]
